  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3175607550" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3175607550" />
    <a title="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22976975-kevin-lopez-on-sabbatical"><img alt="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1376112680p2/22976975.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3175607550?book_show_action=true">Apr 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)" href="/user/show/22976975-kevin-lopez-on-sabbatical">Kevin Lopez (on sabbatical)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22976975-kevin-lopez-on-sabbatical?shelf=science-biology-and-chemistry">science-biology-and-chemistry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22976975-kevin-lopez-on-sabbatical?shelf=history-of-science">history-of-science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3175607550" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5376688748119379560">“<i>
  <strong>Here, in the estuarine plains of criss-crossing information, history, society, and culture collide and intersect with genetics, like tides. Some waves cancel each other, while others reinforce each other. No force is particularly strong—but their combined effect produces the unique and rippled landscape that we call an individual’s identity.</strong>
</i>”<br/><br/>“<i>
  <strong>Normalcy is the antithesis of evolution.</strong>
</i>”<br/><br/>“The Gene: An Intimate History” by Siddhartha Mukherjee is a comprehensive, relentlessly informative and </span>
  <span id="freeText5376688748119379560" style="display:none">“<i>
  <strong>Here, in the estuarine plains of criss-crossing information, history, society, and culture collide and intersect with genetics, like tides. Some waves cancel each other, while others reinforce each other. No force is particularly strong—but their combined effect produces the unique and rippled landscape that we call an individual’s identity.</strong>
</i>”<br /><br />“<i>
  <strong>Normalcy is the antithesis of evolution.</strong>
</i>”<br /><br />“The Gene: An Intimate History” by Siddhartha Mukherjee is a comprehensive, relentlessly informative and entertaining history of the gene, and of all the myriad domains that it touches upon: the essence of family, heredity, fate, creativity, individuality, humanity, and life itself—indeed, of the very nature and meaning of being alive, of being born, of dying, and of all the untold generations that will succeed us and inherit our legacy. <br /><br />“<i>
  <strong>The genome is only a mirror for the breadth or narrowness of human imagination.</strong>
</i>”<br /><br />Throughout this book, Mukherjee systematically traces the vastly differing theories and conceptualizations of the genesis and reproduction of life across the past 2,500 years of human thought—a lineage of lineage, if you will—from Pythagoras and Aristotle in antiquity to Darwin and Mendel in the mid-19th century; from Francis Galton and the insidious spread of the eugenics movement in the early-20th century to its grisly apotheosis during the Holocaust; from Watson, Crick, Wilkins and Franklin’s discovery of the double-helix structure of DNA to the first successful gene-cloning experiment; from the Human Genome Project in the 1990s to present-day bioethical debates over the uses of stem cells and cutting-edge gene-editing technologies like CRISPR. Throughout, Mukherjee moves fluidly from dispassionate scientific observer to introspective participant, offering personal reflections on his family’s history of mental illness, all the while continuing to inform, instruct and explicate, clearly elucidating not only the science and the resultant technologies, but also all of the thorny moral, political, philosophical, and societal implications of what is undoubtedly the most potentially transformative and transcendent—not to say destructive and dangerous—idea of our time: the gene. The very key to life itself.<br /><br />“<i>In 1990, writing about the Human Genome Project, the geneticist John Sulston wondered about <strong>the philosophical quandary raised by an intelligent organism that has ‘learned to read its own instructions.’ But an infinitely deeper quandary is raised when an intelligent organism learns to write its own instructions. If genes determine the nature and fate of an organism, and if organisms now begin to determine the nature and fate of their genes, then a circle of logic closes on itself. Once we start thinking of genes as destiny, manifest, then it is inevitable to begin imagining the human genome as manifest destiny.</strong></i>”<br /><br /><br />“The Gene” is a fascinating tour through the history, people, and ideas that revolutionized our notion of what it means to be human, to live, and which are, even now, illuminating the pathway to a better understanding of ourselves and our fellow living beings. <br /><br /><br />Five out of five stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5376688748119379560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


